{"title":"TOP-ReID: Multi-spectral Object Re-Identification with Token Permutation","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Multi-spectral ReID must fuse RGB/NIR/TIR features despite large cross-spectral distribution gaps; most Transformer-based ReID pipelines rely mainly on class-token global features and underuse local patch information, yielding weak alignment and fusion.","method":"Use three independent ViT streams to preserve spectrum-specific tokens, then apply a cyclic Token Permutation Module (TPM) that runs three consecutive permutations where each spectrum’s class token performs multi-head cross-attention over another spectrum’s patch tokens (e.g., RGB cls → NIR patches → TIR patches, then back to own patches), with LayerNorm-stabilized queries/keys. The permuted class tokens are concatenated as the fused descriptor. This design lets global class tokens ingest local details from other spectra and implicitly aligns spatial features across spectra, outperforming simple concatenation/fusion (e.g., ablations show notable gains)."},{"problem":"Cross-spectral distribution gaps and missing-spectral conditions (at training or inference) degrade multi-spectral ReID performance and complicate unified feature learning.","method":"Introduce a Complementary Reconstruction Module (CRM) that performs dense token-level reconstruction across spectra via Transformer-based reconstruction blocks. For each stream, CRM reconstructs the other spectra’s tokens and applies MSE constraints against real tokens to reduce distribution gaps. At inference, when any spectrum is missing, CRM dynamically reconstructs its tokens from the available streams and feeds them into TPM so the cyclic permutation proceeds normally. Token-level reconstruction proves superior to pixel-level methods and enables robust performance under missing-spectral scenarios."}]}
